Following the death of his wife, he began a relationship with Ruth Loah, 81, his long-time secretary and they are still together.

'Ruth saved my life,' said Schmidt, who was chancellor of Germany from 1974 until 1982.

During his time as West Germany's chancellor he lead the country through Cold War tensions and a bloody wave of terror by far-left radicals, the Red Army Faction.  

He won the Iron Cross for his services in WWII which included action on both the eastern and western fronts. 

Last year, he revealed he had stashed 38,000 menthol cigarettes in his home because of fears the EU would try to ban them.

He is well known for being excused for smoking in places where it is banned.

Der Spiegel reported that the 40-a-day smoker has in the past managed to get away with it both in television studios and congress halls.

